description:
Using MongoDB version 2.4.5 and PHP driver version 1.4.2:

We are seeing new ReplicaSet connections via MongoClient hang when a secondary in the cluster is creating indexes during an initial sync.

The bug is fairly easy to reproduce. 

We run the following code continuously while letting a secondary to an initialSync:

{code}
<?php

date_default_timezone_set('America/Los_Angeles');

while ( true ) {

        //Timestamp
        echo date("D F d H:i:s\n");

        $m = new MongoClient("mongodb://<USER>:<PW>@XYZ1:PORT,XYZ2:PORT/DB", array("replicaSet" => "RS"));
        $connections = $m->getConnections();
        foreach($connections as $con)
        {
                $closed = $m->close( $con['hash'] );
                echo $closed ? "ok" : "failed", "\n";
        }
        sleep(5);
}       
?>
{code}

Once the secondary starts building indexes the code hangs on the MongoClient line.

Below are the log lines from the mongod during the start of an index build, which is when the test code begins to hang:

{code}
Fri Jul 26 13:26:56.031 [rsSync] build index sl-data-prod-hsessions.vc_session_histories { _id: 1 }
Fri Jul 26 13:26:56.179 [conn426] end connection 199.116.73.110:61248 (7 connections now open)
Fri Jul 26 13:27:02.475 [initandlisten] connection accepted from 199.116.73.110:61311 #427 (8 connections now open)
Fri Jul 26 13:27:02.655 [conn427]  authenticate db: sl-data-prod-hsessions { authenticate: 1, user: "test", nonce: "9987818551f74ef0", key: "4b1537f079238b94047c92460d136ed0" }
Fri Jul 26 13:27:06.007 [rsSync] 		Index: (1/3) External Sort Progress: 190300/18560872	1%
{code}

Segfaults occurred while processing a BSON string and copying the byte sequence from the BSON buffer into a {{char*}} using PHP's {{ZVAL_STRINGL}} macro, which in turn utilizes {{_estrndup()}} and {{memcpy()}}. These were caused by the driver encountering {{0}} as the int32 length prefix of a BSON string. According to the [spec|http://bsonspec.org/#/specification], this length should include the null byte of the string, so we'd expect it to at least be {{1}} for an empty string. The driver does have a bug when checking for an invalid length in [line 912 of bson.c|https://github.com/mongodb/mongo-php-driver/blob/1.3.7/bson.c#L912]. The {{INVALID_STRING_LEN}} macro is defined in [line 45 of bson.h|https://github.com/mongodb/mongo-php-driver/blob/1.3.7/bson.h#L45]:

{code}
#define INVALID_STRING_LEN(len) (len < 0 || len > (64*1024*1024))
{code}

If {{len}} is {{0}}, this will fail to consider it invalid and the driver will *not* throw an exception and instead proceed to copy {{(len - 1)}} bytes from the buffer, attempting to omit the null byte:

{code}
if (INVALID_STRING_LEN(len)) {
    zval_ptr_dtor(&value);
    zend_throw_exception_ex(mongo_ce_CursorException, 0 TSRMLS_CC, "invalid string length for key \"%s\": %d", name, len);
    return 0;
}
buf += INT_32;

ZVAL_STRINGL(value, buf, len-1, 1);
buf += len;
{code}

Ultimately, this results in a very large unsigned integer being passed to {{memcpy()}} and causes a segfault.

At a glance, I believe BSON decoding of code (with and without scopes) and the deprecated DB pointer type may also be affected.

Using collection->update with the mongo $inc operator, the field 
value is incremented incorrectly.  The field is incremented by double the 
incremental value.

For example:

$collection->update(array('_id' => '123'), array('$inc'=> array('pageviews' => 
1)), array('upsert' => true));

If pageviews = 0, pageviews would = 2 after the update statement.  If pageviews = 
1, pageviews would = 3 after the update statement.


Here is a test script:

<?php
$m = new MongoClient();
$db = $m->selectDB('test');
$collection = $db->selectCollection('tracking');
$collection->update(array('_id' => '123'), array('$inc'=> array('pageviews' => 1)), array('upsert' => true));

When storing an 'err' property in a document, when iterating over the documents the driver will throw a MongoCursorException with the value of this property as the Exception Message.

Example, I was storing exceptions received from our solr application:

{
   // ...
   err: "Solr HTTP error: HTTP request failed"
}

Later, when iterating over these documents, the driver would through the MongoCursorException.

Calling the info method on a dead MongoCursor object causes a page fault.  See the script below to reproduce.

{code:php}
<?php
#################################
# ECHO VERSIONS #################
#################################
echo "PHP: " . phpversion() . "\n";
echo "Mongo Driver: " . phpversion('mongo') . "\n";

##########################################
# CREATE FAILURE CONDITION ###############
##########################################

$connection = new MongoClient('mongodb://localhost:27017');

$connection->test->segfault_demo->insert(array('test' => 1));
$connection->test->segfault_demo->insert(array('test' => 2));
$connection->test->segfault_demo->insert(array('test' => 3));
$connection->test->segfault_demo->insert(array('test' => 4));
$connection->test->segfault_demo->insert(array('test' => 5));
$connection->test->segfault_demo->insert(array('test' => 6));
$connection->test->segfault_demo->insert(array('test' => 7));

$txlogs = $connection->test->segfault_demo->find()->limit(5);

foreach($txlogs as $txlog)  {
  echo ($txlogs->dead() ? "Dead" : "Not Dead") . "\n";
}

################################
# CAUSE SEGFAULT ###############
################################
$txlogs->info();
{code}

Output:
{code:bash}
PHP: 5.3.10-1ubuntu3.9
Mongo Driver: 1.4.5
Not Dead
Not Dead
Not Dead
Not Dead
Not Dead
Segmentation fault
{code}
